article.description: Mike Bibby and the Sacramento Kings  spread the wealth early and often.
article.headline: Five Kings rack up double figures
article.linkText: Miller leads Kings over sluggish Hornets
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings' big men passed as well as their guards, and the whole team shot well against the struggling New Orleans Hornets. Brad Miller had 21 points, 14 rebounds and nine assists to lead the Kings to a 101-90 victory Thursday night. Mike Bibby added 19 points, Bobby Jackson had 18 and Peja Stojakovic 17 for the Kings. "Our big men are some of the best passers in the league. Our offense is run through them and if we get open they get us the ball," Bibby said. "We were just trying to move a lot and that's harder to guard than just regular plays." Front court starters Vlade Divac and Stojakovic combined for eight assists, equaling that of starting guard tandem Bibby and Doug Christie. Divac also had 10 points, hitting four of five shots. New Orleans (17-10) has lost three straight -- all by double-digit margins -- for its worst losing streak of the season. The dry spell has come with new coach Tim Floyd needing only one victory to surpass his personal best for victories in a season. The most he had in any of his three-plus seasons in Chicago was 17. Baron Davis led New Orleans with 23 points. In their first season running a motion offense, the Hornets created open shots on the perimeter. But unlike earlier in the season, they couldn't make them. "It was almost like we were playing like we were afraid to miss a shot or take a shot," Floyd said. "We did have guys who played with effort, just not enough of it. ... It's just a tough period that we're going to have to fight through right now." Sacramento has been running the same style offense effectively for several years and put on a clinic, getting numerous easy baskets off baseline and backdoor cuts, as well as 20 points on the fast break. "Everybody was talking and just rotating. Just that intensity is what got us through tonight," said Miller, who began his career with the Hornets but got little playing time with the team before emerging with Indiana. "This is where it all started. You play 82 games a year and there are certain ones I look forward to every year." The Kings also hit their jump shots for just over 55 percent shooting overall. The Kings scored 22 points from the free-throw line, compared to nine points for New Orleans. The Hornets shot 40 percent, but hit only 36 percent of their shots through the first three periods, after which the Kings led 75-61. "It was hard to tell how good our defense was. When they kept missing shots, they sort of got down," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. The Kings built leads as big as 25 and led 87-67 after Jackson's fade midway through the fourth quarter. The Hornets began 1-for-15 from 3-point range and finished 7-for-31. Shooting guard David Wesley started 0-for-5 from the field, and the Hornets suffered through one five-minute stretch in the opening period without a basket while the Kings scored 13 straight points for a 27-14 lead. Wesley, his team's second leading scorer with a 16.3 average coming in, finished his 1-of-9 half with an airball on a straightaway 3 and a mishandled pass on the fast break, prompting fans near the bench to implore Floyd to pull Wesley from the game. Wesley was 1-of-11 for three points through three periods before finishing strong for 12 points. "We're shooting a lot of 3s and they are not going and that's costing us games," Wesley said. "Our defense is not as good as it was in the beginning and therefore we can't get out and run" the fast break. Jamaal Magloire had 15 points and 13 rebounds for the Hornets, and P.J. Brown had 15 points. The Hornets finished with a 43-40 rebounding edge, but only because of 15 offensive rebounds after 55 missed shots.

Game notes
Saints receiver Joe Horn attended the game and got a loud standing ovation when a Hornets mascot performed a dunk off of a trampoline, pulled out his cell phone, and walked over to Horn's seat to point him out. Horn smiled, stood briefly and waved to the crowd. Horn was fined $30,000 by the NFL this week after celebrating a touchdown catch by making a mock cell phone call. ... The Kings (17-6) are 4-5 on the road.
